From collocations to timeline

This notebook includes functions for building collocation networks and analyzing selected collocations on a timeline.

First, collocations for search terms are fetched from a folder including text files that are already lemmatized (i.e. the corpus). Next, second-order collocations are fetched, i.e., collocates of the collocates are found.

Individual words are then saved as node file, and collocations are saved as edges file, including the z-score as a measure of the weight, which can be exported to Gephi, to build a collocation network.

The part on finding collocations and calculating the weight for them is based on https://kristopherkyle.github.io/corpus-analysis-python/Python_Tutorial_6.html_

In the latter part, selected collocates are fetched from an Excel-file that contains the same texts than the folder mentioned above. These are put on a timeline, and found collocations (per sentence) are summed on monthly basis. Line-diagrams of these timelines are printed.

# Based on https://kristopherkyle.github.io/corpus-analysis-python/Python_Tutorial_6.html

import glob 
import operator

def tokenize(input_string): #input_string = text string
	tokenized = [] #empty list that will be returned

	#these are the punctuation marks in the Brown corpus + '"'
	punct_list = ['','-',',','.',"'",'&','`','?','!',';',':','(',')','$','/','%','*','+','[',']','{','}','"',' " ', '', '|']

	#this is a sample (but potentially incomplete) list of items to replace with spaces
	replace_list = ["\t"]

	#This is a sample (but potentially incomplete) list if items to ignore
	ignore_list = ["", " "]

	#iterate through the punctuation list and delete each item
	for x in punct_list:
		input_string = input_string.replace(x, "") #instead of adding a space before punctuation marks, we will delete them (by replacing with nothing)

	#iterate through the replace list and replace it with a space
	for x in replace_list:
		input_string = input_string.replace(x," ")

	#our examples will be in English, so for now we will lower them
	#this is, of course optional
	input_string = input_string.lower()

	#then we split the string into a list
	input_list = input_string.split(" ")

	for x in input_list:
		if (x not in ignore_list) and len(x) > 1: #if item is not in the ignore list; leaving one-character words out
			tokenized.append(x) #add it to the list "tokenized"
            
	return(tokenized)

def freq_update(tok_list,freq_dict): #this takes a list (tok_list) and a dictionary (freq_dict) as arguments
	for x in tok_list: #for x in list
		if x not in freq_dict: #if x not in dictionary
			freq_dict[x] = 1 #create new entry
		else: #else: add one to entry
			freq_dict[x] += 1

def head(stat_dict,hits = 20,hsort = True,output = False,filename = None, sep = "\t"):
	#first, create sorted list. Presumes that operator has been imported
	sorted_list = sorted(stat_dict.items(),key=operator.itemgetter(1),reverse = hsort)[:hits]

	if output == False and filename == None: #if we aren't writing a file or returning a list
		for x in sorted_list: #iterate through the output
			print(x[0] + "\t" + str(x[1])) #print the sorted list in a nice format

	elif filename is not None: #if a filename was provided
		outf = open(filename,"w") #create a blank file in the working directory using the filename
		outf.write("item\tstatistic") #write header
		for x in sorted_list: #iterate through list
			outf.write("\n" + x[0] + sep + str(x[1])) #write each line to a file using the separator
		outf.flush() #flush the file buffer
		outf.close() #close the file

	if output == True: #if output is true
		return(sorted_list) #return the sorted list

import glob
import re

def corpus_context_freq(dir_name, target, nleft=5, nright=5):
    left_freq = {}  # frequency of items to the left
    right_freq = {}  # frequency of items to the right
    combined_freq = {}  # combined left and right frequency
    target_freq = {}  # frequency dictionary for all target hits
    corp_freq = {}  # total frequency for all words

    # create a list that includes all files in the dir_name folder that end in ".txt"
    filenames = glob.glob(dir_name + "/*.txt")
    # print(filenames)
    # iterate through each file:
    for filename in filenames:
        # open the file as a string
        wholetext = open(filename, errors="ignore", encoding="utf-8").read()
        for text in wholetext.split("\n"):
            tok_list = tokenize(text)
            for idx, x in enumerate(tok_list):  # iterate through token list using the enumerate function. idx = list index, x = list item
                freq_update([x], corp_freq)  # update the corpus frequency for all words
                hit = False  # set Boolean value to False
                if type(target) == str and target == x:  # If the target is a string and we have a match
                    hit = True  # then we have a search hit
                elif type(target) == list and x in target:  # if the target is a list and the current word is in the list
                    hit = True  # then we have a search hit

                if hit:  # if we have a search hit:
                    #print(" ".join(tok_list))
                    if idx < nleft:  # deal with left context if search term comes early in a text
                        left = tok_list[:idx]  # get x number of words before the current one (based on nleft)
                        freq_update(left, left_freq)  # update frequency dictionary for the left context
                        freq_update(left, combined_freq)  # update frequency dictionary for all contexts

                    
                    else:
                        left = tok_list[idx - nleft:idx]  # get x number of words before the current one (based on nleft)
                        freq_update(left, left_freq)  # update frequency dictionary for the left context
                        freq_update(left, combined_freq)  # update frequency dictionary for all contexts

                    t = x  # current token is the target term
                    freq_update([t], target_freq)  # update target frequency

                    right = tok_list[idx + 1:idx + nright + 1]  # get x number of words after the current one (based on nright)
                    freq_update(right, right_freq)  # update frequency dictionary for the right context
                    freq_update(right, combined_freq)  # update frequency dictionary for all contexts

    output_dict = {"left_freq": left_freq, "right_freq": right_freq, "combined_freq": combined_freq, "target_freq": target_freq, "corp_freq": corp_freq}
    return output_dict
In[6]:
import math

def soa(freq_dict,cut_off = 5, exp_freq_corr = True, window_size = 5 + 5):
    mi = {}
    mi2 = {}
    mi3 = {}
    mu = {}
    z_score = {}
    tscore = {}
    faith_coll_cue = {}
    faith_target_cue = {}
    deltap_coll_cue = {}
    deltap_target_cue = {}
    
    corpus_size = sum(freq_dict["corp_freq"].values()) #get the size of the corpus by summing the frequency of all words . This will stay consistent for all iterations below
    target_freq = sum(freq_dict["target_freq"].values()) #get the total number of corpus hits for all forms of the target item. This will stay consistent for all iterations below

    #iterate through context hits
    for collocate in freq_dict["combined_freq"]:
        observed = freq_dict["combined_freq"][collocate] #frequency of target coocurring with collocate
        collocate_freq = freq_dict["corp_freq"][collocate] #Total frequency of collocate in corpus
        if freq_dict["combined_freq"][collocate] >= cut_off: #check to make sure that the collocate occurs frequently enough to surpass the threshold
            if exp_freq_corr:
                expected = ((target_freq * collocate_freq * window_size)/corpus_size)
            else:    
                expected = ((target_freq * collocate_freq)/corpus_size)

            # The following are from Brezina 2013, p. 72 -->

            mu[collocate] = observed / expected

            mi2[collocate] = math.log2((observed ** 2) / expected)

            mi3[collocate] = math.log2((observed ** 3) / expected)

            z_score[collocate] = (observed - expected) / math.sqrt(expected)

            # --< 

            tscore[collocate] = (observed-expected)/(math.sqrt(observed)) #calcuate T score and add it to dict



	#create output dictionary:
    output_dict = {"mu": mu, "mi" : mi, "mi2" : mi, "mi3": mi3, "z_score" : z_score, "tscore" : tscore, "faith_coll_cue" : faith_coll_cue, "faith_target_cue" : faith_target_cue, "deltap_coll_cue" : deltap_coll_cue, "deltap_target_cue" : deltap_target_cue}
    return(output_dict)

import pandas as pd

def get_soas(match:str, path):
    freqs = corpus_context_freq(path, match)
    soas = pd.DataFrame(soa(freqs)).reset_index()
    soas = soas.rename(columns={'index': 'collocate'})
    soas["match"] = match
    cols = soas.columns.tolist()
    cols = cols[-1:] + cols[:-1]
    soas = soas[cols]

    soas = soas.sort_values(by=[tops], ascending=False)
    return soas

In[4]:
def extract_collocations(df, collocates_list, window_size=5):
    ''' Checks if searched collocate exists in sentence, and adds one, then sums up monthly'''
    # Convert collocates_list to a set of frozensets for fast lookups
    collocates_set = {frozenset(collocate) for collocate in collocates_list}
    
    # Dictionary to count collocate appearances per month
    monthly_counts = defaultdict(lambda: Counter())

    for _, row in df.iterrows():
        try:
            words = row['sentence_lemmas'].lower().split()  # Normalize to lowercase
            date = row['text_issue_date'][:7]  # Extract YYYY-MM
            
            found_collocates = set()  # Track collocates found in this row

            for i in range(len(words)):
                window = words[max(0, i - window_size):i] + words[i + 1:min(len(words), i + 1 + window_size)]
                window_set = set(window)  # Convert window to a set for fast lookup

                for collocate in collocates_set:
                    if collocate.issubset(window_set):  # Check if collocate is present
                        found_collocates.add("_".join(sorted(collocate)))  # Store the found collocate
            
            # Add each found collocate only once per row
            for collocate in found_collocates:
                monthly_counts[date][collocate] += 1

        except Exception as e:
            print("Exception:", e, "Row:", row)

    # Convert to DataFrame
    monthly_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(monthly_counts, orient="index").fillna(0).astype(int)
    monthly_df.index.name = "Month"

    return monthly_df

# Function to clean sentence_lemmas column
def clean_lemmas(text):
    try:
        return re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z0-9\s]', '', text).strip()
    except:
        print("Exception, ", text)
        return

# Function to standardize date format
def fix_date_format(date):
    try:
        return pd.to_datetime(date, errors='coerce').strftime('%Y-%m-%d')
    except:
        return None
In[6]:
def fill_missing_months(df, start_month="2017-01", end_month="2021-12"):
    # Ensure index is in datetime format
    df.index = pd.to_datetime(df.index, format="%Y-%m")

    # Generate a complete range of months
    all_months = pd.date_range(start=start_month, end=end_month, freq="MS")

    # Reindex the DataFrame, filling missing months with 0
    df = df.reindex(all_months, fill_value=0)

    # Convert index back to YYYY-MM format as string
    df.index = df.index.strftime("%Y-%m")

    # Ensure index name is kept
    df.index.name = "Month"

    return df

def save_xls(list_dfs, xls_path):
    with ExcelWriter(xls_path) as writer:
        for n, df in enumerate(list_dfs):
            df.to_excel(writer,'sheet%s' % n)

def make_tabs(df, title, sheets_n_colls, sample=None, xls_path="./Top_colls/"):
    if sample:
        data = df.sample(n=sample, random_state=1)
    else:
        data = df
    df['sentence_lemmas'] = df['sentence_lemmas'].apply(clean_lemmas)
    df['text_issue_date'] = df['text_issue_date'].apply(fix_date_format)
    dict_df = {}
    for sheet in sheets_n_colls.keys():
        collocates_list = sheets_n_colls[sheet]
        monthly_collocates = extract_collocations(df, collocates_list)
        df_filled = fill_missing_months(monthly_collocates)
        #df_filled[f'{sheet}_sum']=df[df.columns].sum(axis=1)
        dict_df[sheet] = df_filled
    
    writer = ExcelWriter(xls_path + f'monthly_{title}.xlsx')
    for key in dict_df.keys():
        dict_df[key].to_excel(writer, sheet_name=key)
    writer.close()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

def makeplots(dfs=dfs, 
              selected_sheets=group1, 
              xcol='Month', 
              y_var='Collocation', 
              sum_specifier="Monthly",
              path="From collocation to timeline", 
              title="Title"):
    
    if len(selected_sheets) == 1:
        rows, cols = 1,1
    else:
        cols = 2
        if len(selected_sheets) % 2 == 0:
            rows = int(len(selected_sheets) / 2)
        else:
            rows = int(len(selected_sheets) / 2) + 1
    
    # Set up the grid
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, cols, figsize=(15, 15))
    axes = axes.flatten()  # Flatten to iterate easily

    for i, sheet_name in enumerate(selected_sheets):
        if sheet_name in dfs:
            df = dfs[sheet_name]
        
            # Reshape data for seaborn
            df_melted = df.melt(id_vars=[xcol], var_name=y_var, value_name="Sum")
        
            # Plot
            sns.lineplot(data=df_melted, x=xcol, y="Sum", hue=y_var, ax=axes[i])
            axes[i].set_title(sheet_name)
            axes[i].set_xlabel(xcol)
            axes[i].set_ylabel(f"{sum_specifier} Sum")


            axes[i].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=90)
            axes[i].tick_params(axis='x', labelsize=8)
            plt.suptitle(title, fontsize=16)

    # Adjust layout
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(f"./{path}/{title}.svg", format="svg", bbox_inches="tight")
    plt.show()

file_path = "./From collocation to timeline/titles&sterms_bd_copy.xlsx"  # Change this to your actual file path
sheets = pd.ExcelFile(file_path).sheet_names  # Get sheet names

# Read sheets into a list of DataFrames
dfs = [pd.read_excel(file_path, sheet_name=sheet) for sheet in sheets]

monthly_dfs = []
for df in dfs:
    df["Month"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Month"], format="%Y-%m-%d", errors="coerce")  # Convert to datetime
    df = df.resample("M", on="Month").sum().reset_index()  # Group by month & sum
    df["Month"] = df["Month"].dt.strftime("%Y-%m")  # Format as YYYY-MM (clean output)
    monthly_dfs.append(df)
